article.description: Gwen Jackson scored 32 points in just 23 minutes helping fifth-ranked Tennessee remain undefeated in Southeastern Conference play with a 94-53 rout of Florida.
article.headline: Lady Vols outrebound Gators 53-31
article.linkText: Gators can't stop Jackson, and in turn, Lady Vols
article.story:
GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida's lineup of underclassmen was
no match for Tennessee's star senior.

	   Gwen Jackson scored a career-high 32 points as the No. 5 Lady
Vols dominated the overmatched Gators 94-53 on Sunday.

	   Exploiting the young and inexperienced Gators -- who started four
freshmen and a sophomore -- mostly in the lane, Jackson shot
13-of-18 from the floor and had seven rebounds. She also went
2-of-3 from 3-point range and made her four free-throw attempts.

	   "The shots were falling and I was feeling it,'' said Jackson,
who scored 18 of her points on layups or short jumpers. "My
teammates were getting me the ball, and in the game today,
everything clicked.''

	   Shanna Zolman added a career-high 19 points for Tennessee (14-3,
3-0 Southeastern Conference), which shot 52 percent for the game
and built a 52-17 halftime lead.

	   Jackson scored 22 in the first half -- more than the Gators (8-8,
0-4), who lost their fourth in a row and are off to their worst
conference start in 16 seasons.

	   "Tennessee is a very veteran team with a lot of experience,''
Florida coach Carolyn Peck said. "Playing them is also a good
experience for our young team to go through right now. You learn
through experience, by getting out there and doing it, not just
sitting and watching.''

	   Zolman was 7-of-12 shooting, including 4-of-5 from 3-point
range. Tennessee finished 11-of-16 from beyond the arc.

	   "We have more 3-point weapons than we've ever had, and I think
that certainly spreads the defense out,'' Tennessee coach Pat
Summitt said. "I think they're in love with the 3, and I don't see
that changing. I think their shot selection has been solid.''

	   The Vols beat Florida outside and inside, and outrebounded the
Gators 53-31.

	   Florida made just seven shots in the first half and finished
shooting 32.8 percent. The Gators played better in the second half,
but that came with many Vols starters on the bench.

	   Jackson played just 23 minutes, and each of Tennessee's 11
players scored.

	   "We didn't fold up our tents,'' Peck said. "We had breakdowns,
but the effort was there. Everyone went out there and gave their
all. I think the main thing was we got over our fear.''

	   Tishona Gregory and Bernice Mosby had 12 points each, while
Sarah Lowe added 10 for the Gators. The 41-point loss marked the
first time Florida has lost three games in a row by more than 35
points. In the four-game losing streak, the Gators have combined to
lose by 125 points.

	   "The news media and people outside need to understand that the
differential in the score isn't indicative of how good this team is
going to be,'' Peck said. "That's what we're working on is how
good this team is going to be.''
